on?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreasing calcium intake","Decreasing citrus fruit intake","Increasing animal protein intake","Increasing fluid intake","Increasing sodium intake"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most important preventive measure for kidney stones is \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing fluid intake\u003C/strong\u003E to maintain adequate hydration. This dilutes urinary solutes and reduces the risk of crystal formation.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing sodium intake\u003C/strong\u003E actually promotes stone formation by increasing urinary calcium excretion. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreasing animal protein intake\u003C/strong\u003E raises urinary calcium and decreases citrate, both of which increase stone risk.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreasing calcium intake\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as this can paradoxically increase stone risk by promoting oxalate absorption. \u003Cstrong\u003EDecreasing citrus fruit intake\u003C/strong\u003E would reduce urinary citrate, an important inhibitor of calcium stone formation.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EOther preventive measures include maintaining a healthy weight and limiting sodium intake to less than 2300 mg per day.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Increased fluid intake reduces risk of kidney stone formation by diluting urinary solutes","High sodium and animal protein intake increase urinary calcium excretion and stone risk","Dietary modifications are key preventive measures for kidney stones"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Fontenelle LF, Sarti TD. Kidney Stones: Treatment and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 